The quality issues noted and the extraction or transformation that needs to be done¶

duration_sec - fine as integer, and it can be further converted to hours and minutes

start_time - should be date time , date (day and month) and time(hour) can be extracted

end_time - should be date time, date (day and month) and time (hour) can be extracted

start_station_id - should be object

start_station_name - fine as object

start_station_latitude - fine as float64

start_station_longitude - fine as float64

end_station_id - should be object

end_station_name- fine as object

end_station_latitude -fine as float64

end_station_longitude - fine as float64

bike_id- should be object

user_type - should be category

member_birth_year - fine as integer, age can be extracted from it

member_gender - should be category

bike_share_for_all_trip - should be category

Missing values will be dropped for start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_id, start_station_name, member_birth_year, member_gender because they can't be replaced and the amount is insignificant compared to the whole dataset(about 4.5%)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The cleaned dataset has 174752 features and 29 columns which contains information about the duration, start time, end time of bike trips, the types of users, names of start and end stations with their ids, latitude and longitude, the id of the bikes used, birth year. age and genders of the members

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in how long a trip takes, the kind of users that are involved in the trips, the age groups and genders, the day of the week or time of the day or year the trips are taken and what determines the bike sharing for all trips

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the duration, start and end time, user type, gender, age and bike share for all trip will help support my invstigation

Conclusion¶

The types of users we have are subscribers and customers. Subscribers prefer riding during the week, at the beginning and end of work hours because they are the working class people and they ride their bikes to thier workplaces. Also, the preferred start stations constitute the end stations, which supports the insight that the users are routine riders that use the stations everyday to go to thier work places. Customers prefer ridng on weekends probably because they just ride for fun and don't use it routinely, they also spend more time on their rides because they are probably not paying or they want to use all they can get on free versions before going ahead to subscribe. Only subscribers share their trips, it is possible that there is no sharing feature for customers i.e. no sharing feature on the free version until you subscribe. Although, most subscribers still don't share because they are the working class and probably do not have time to share and would prefer to do something else with their time. Users spend more time riding in the midnight (early hours of the day) compared to the other hours of the day.
